# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbon-monoxide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-2-dioxetanedione] The chemical compound **1,2-dioxetanedione**, or **1,2-dioxacyclobutane-3,4-dione**, often called **peroxyacid ester**, is an unstable oxide of carbon (an oxocarbon) with formula C2O4.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-2-dioxetanedione] It can be viewed as a double ketone of 1,2-dioxetane (1,2-dioxacyclobutane), or a cyclic dimer of carbon dioxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-2-dioxetanedione] In ordinary conditions, it quickly decomposes to carbon dioxide (CO2) even at 180 K (−93.1 °C), but can be detected by mass spectrometry and other techniques.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-2-dioxetanedione] 1,2-Dioxetanedione is an intermediate in the chemoluminescent reactions used in glowsticks.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-2-dioxetanedione] The decomposition proceeds via a paramagnetic oxalate biradical intermediate.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-5-trioxanetrione] The chemical compound **1,3,5-trioxanetrione**, or **1,3,5-trioxacyclohexane-2,4,6-trione** is an unstable oxide of carbon with formula C3O6.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-5-trioxanetrione] It can be considered a cyclic trimer of carbon dioxide (CO2) or as a triple ketone of 1,3,5-trioxane (1,3,5-trioxacyclohexane).
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-5-trioxanetrione] Trioxanetrione has been synthesized but is exceedingly unstable, with a half-life of approximately 40 min at −40 °C.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-dioxetanedione] The chemical compound **1,3-dioxetanedione**, or **1,3-dioxacyclobutane-2,4-dione**, also known as **dicarbonic anhydride**, is a hypothetical oxide of carbon with formula C2O4.
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-dioxetanedione] It can be considered a cyclic dimer of carbon dioxide (CO2) or as a double ketone of 1,3-dioxetane (1,3-dioxacyclobutane).
[src:carbon-monoxide/1-3-dioxetanedione] Theoretical calculations indicate that the compound would be extremely unstable at room temperature (half-life of less than 1.1 μs) but may be stable at −196 °C.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-AG, unlike anandamide (another endocannabinoid), is present at relatively high levels in the central nervous system; it is the most abundant molecular species of monoacylglycerol found in mouse and rat brain (~5–10 nmol/g tissue).
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] Detection of 2-AG in brain tissue is complicated by the relative ease of its isomerization to 1-AG during standard lipid extraction conditions.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] It has been found in bovine as well as human milk.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-AG was discovered by Raphael Mechoulam and his student Shimon Ben-Shabat.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-AG was a known chemical compound but its occurrence in mammals and its affinity for the cannabinoid receptors were first described in 1994–1995.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-Arachidonoylglycerol, next with Anandamide, was the second endocannabinoid discovered.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] The cannabinoid established the existence of a cannabinoid neuromodulatory system in the nervous system.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] Unlike anandamide, formation of 2-AG is calcium-dependent and is mediated by the activities of phospholipase C (PLC) and diacylglycerol lipase (DAGL).
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-AG acts as a full agonist at the CB1 receptor.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] At a concentration of 0.3 nM, 2-AG induces a rapid, transient increase in intracellular free calcium in NG108-15 neuroblastoma X glioma cells through a CB1 receptor-dependent mechanism.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-AG is hydrolyzed *in vitro* by monoacylglycerol lipase (MAGL), fatty acid amide hydrolase (FAAH), and the uncharacterized serine hydrolase enzymes ABHD2, ABHD6 and ABHD12.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] The exact contribution of each of these enzymes to the termination of 2-AG signaling *in vivo* is unknown, though it is estimated that MAGL is responsible for ~85% of this activity in the brain.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] There have been identified transport proteins for 2-arachidonoylglycerol and anandamide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] These include the heat shock proteins (Hsp70s) and fatty acid binding proteins (FABPs).
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] 2-Arachidonoylglycerol is synthesized from arachidonic acid-containing diacylglycerol (DAG), which is derived from the increase of inositol phospholipid metabolism by the action of diacylglycerol lipase.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonoylglycerol] The molecule can also be formed from pathways like the hydrolysis derived (by diglyceride) from both phosphatidylcholine (PC) and phosphatidic acid (PAs) by the action of DAG lipase and the hydrolysis of arachidonic acid-containing lysophosphatidic acid by the action of a phosphatase.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] Lumír Hanuš, Saleh Abu-Lafi, Ester Fride, Aviva Breuer, Zvi Vogel, Deborah E.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] Shalev, Irina Kustanovich, and Raphael Mechoulam found the endogenous agonist of the cannabinoid receptor type 1 (CB1) in 2000.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] The discovery was 100 gram of porcine brain, (approximately a single brain) was added to a mixture of 200 mL of chloroform and 200 mL of methanol and mixed in a laboratory blender for 2 minutes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] 100 mL of Water was then added, and the mixing process continued for another minute.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] Two layers then formed and the layer of water-methanol was separated and evaporated when pressure was reduced.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] Synaptosomal membranes were prepared from 250g of the brains of Sabra male rats.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] A Hewlett Packard G 1800B GCD system that has a HP-5971 GC with electron ionization detector was used.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] The production of the endocannabinoid is enhanced in normal, but not in endothelium-denuded rat aorta on reacting with carbachol, a parasympathomimetic drug.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] It potently reduces blood pressure in rats and may represent an endothelium-derived hypotension factor.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] 2-Arachidonyl glyceryl ether's structure can be determined by mass spectrometry and Rutherford backscattering spectrometry.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] It was confirmed by comparison with a synthetic sample of the endocannabinoid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] It binds to the Cannabinoid receptor type 1 (*Ki = 21.2 ± 0.5 nM*), which causes sedation, hypothermia, intestinal immobility, and mild antinociception in mice.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] The endocannabinoid exhibits Ki values of 21.2 nM and >3 μM at the Cannabinoid receptor type 1 and the peripheral cannabinoid receptors.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] The presence of 2-AGE in body tissue is disputed.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] Although a research group from Teikyo University, Kanagawa, Japan could not detect it in the brains of mice, hamsters, guinea-pigs or pigs, two other research groups successfully detected it in animal tissues.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] 2-AGE binds with a Ki of 21 nM to the CB1 receptor and 480 nM to the CB2 receptor.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] It shows agonistic behaviour on both receptors and is a partial agonist for the TRPV1 channel.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] After binding to CB2 receptors it inhibits adenylate cyclase and stimulates ERK-MAPK and regulates calcium transients.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] In comparison to 2-arachidonoyl glycerol, noladin is metabolically more stable resulting in a longer half-life.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-arachidonyl-glyceryl-ether] It lowers Intraocular pressure, increases the uptake of GABA in the globus pallidus of rats and is neuroprotective by binding to and activation of PPARα.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] 2-Methoxyethanol is used as a solvent for many different purposes such as varnishes, dyes, and resins.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] It is also used as an additive in airplane deicing solutions.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] In organometallic chemistry it is commonly used for the synthesis of Vaska's complex and related compounds such as carbonylchlorohydridotris(triphenylphosphine)ruthenium (II).
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] During these reactions the alcohol acts as a source of hydride and carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] 2-Methoxyethanol is toxic to the bone marrow and testicles.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] Workers exposed to high levels are at risk for granulocytopenia, macrocytic anemia, oligospermia, and azoospermia.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] The methoxyethanol is converted by alcohol dehydrogenase into methoxyacetic acid which is the substance which causes the harmful effects.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] Both ethanol and acetate have a protecting effect.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] The methoxyacetate can enter the Krebs cycle where it forms methoxycitrate.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] In 2024, a group led by researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology reported the discovery of 2-methoxyethanol in a star-forming region within the nebula NGC 6334.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] The discovery was made by examining in the laboratory the spectral signature of 2-methoxyethanol as the molecule was made to rotate.
[src:carbon-monoxide/2-methoxyethanol] This signature was then sought in observational data for the region collected by the Atacama Large Millimeter Array, and 25 of its spectral lines were detected, constituting a secure identification of the molecule in the astronomical data.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The most common source of carbon monoxide is the partial combustion of carbon-containing compounds.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Numerous environmental and biological sources generate carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In industry, carbon monoxide is important in the production of many compounds, including drugs, fragrances, and fuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] CO is one of the most acutely toxic contaminants affecting indoor air quality.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] CO may be emitted from tobacco smoke and generated from malfunctioning fuel-burning stoves (wood, kerosene, natural gas, propane) and fuel-burning heating systems (wood, oil, natural gas) and from blocked flues connected to these appliances.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide poisoning is the most common type of fatal air poisoning in many countries.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has important biological roles across biological kingdoms.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It is produced by many organisms, including humans.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In mammalian physiology, carbon monoxide is a classical example of hormesis where low concentrations serve as an endogenous neurotransmitter (gasotransmitter) and high concentrations are toxic, resulting in carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It is isoelectronic with both cyanide anion CN− and molecular nitrogen N2.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is the simplest oxocarbon and is isoelectronic with other triply bonded diatomic species possessing 10 valence electrons, including the cyanide anion, the nitrosonium cation, boron monofluoride and molecular nitrogen.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It has a molar mass of 28.0, which, according to the ideal gas law, makes it slightly less dense than air, whose average molar mass is 28.8.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The carbon and oxygen are connected by a triple bond that consists of a net two pi bonds and one sigma bond.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The bond length between the carbon atom and the oxygen atom is 112.8 pm.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This bond length is consistent with a triple bond, as in molecular nitrogen (N2), which has a similar bond length (109.76 pm) and nearly the same molecular mass.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon–oxygen double bonds are significantly longer, 120.8 pm in formaldehyde, for example.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The boiling point (82 K) and melting point (68 K) are very similar to those of N2 (77 K and 63 K, respectively).
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The bond-dissociation energy of 1072 kJ/mol is stronger than that of N2 (942 kJ/mol) and represents the strongest chemical bond known.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The ground electronic state of carbon monoxide is a singlet state, since there are no unpaired electrons.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The strength of the C≡O bond in carbon monoxide is indicated by the high frequency of its vibration, 2143 cm−1.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] For comparison, organic carbonyls such as ketones and esters absorb at around 1700 cm−1.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon and oxygen together have a total of 10 electrons in the valence shell.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Following the octet rule for both carbon and oxygen, the two atoms form a triple bond, with six shared electrons in three bonding molecular orbitals, rather than the usual double bond found in organic carbonyl compounds.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Since four of the shared electrons come from the oxygen atom and only two from carbon, one bonding orbital is occupied by two electrons from oxygen, forming a dative or dipolar bond.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This causes a C←O polarization of the molecule, with a small negative charge on carbon and a small positive charge on oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The other two bonding orbitals are each occupied by one electron from carbon and one from oxygen, forming (polar) covalent bonds with a reverse C→O polarization since oxygen is more electronegative than carbon.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the free carbon monoxide molecule, a net negative charge δ− remains at the carbon end and the molecule has a small dipole moment of 0.122 D.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The molecule is therefore asymmetric: oxygen is more electron dense than carbon and is also slightly positively charged, unlike the negative carbon.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has a computed fractional bond order of 2.6, indicating that the "third" bond is important but constitutes somewhat less than a full bond.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Thus, in valence bond terms, −C≡O+ is the most important structure, while :C=O is non-octet, but has a neutral formal charge on each atom and represents the second most important resonance contributor.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Because of the lone pair and divalence of carbon in this resonance structure, carbon monoxide is often considered to be an extraordinarily stabilized carbene.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Isocyanides are compounds in which the O is replaced by an NR (R = alkyl or aryl) group and have a similar bonding scheme.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] If carbon monoxide acts as a ligand, the polarity of the dipole may reverse with a net negative charge on the oxygen end, depending on the structure of the coordination complex.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] See also the section *"Coordination chemistry"* below.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Theoretical and experimental studies show that, despite the greater electronegativity of oxygen, the dipole moment points from the more-negative carbon end to the more-positive oxygen end.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The three bonds are in fact polar covalent bonds that are strongly polarized.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The calculated polarization toward the oxygen atom is 71% for the σ-bond and 77% for both π-bonds.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The oxidation state of carbon in carbon monoxide is +2 in each of these structures.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It is calculated by counting all the bonding electrons as belonging to the more electronegative oxygen.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Only the two non-bonding electrons on carbon are assigned to carbon.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In this count, carbon then has only two valence electrons in the molecule, versus four in the free atom.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide occurs in many environments, usually in trace levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Photochemical degradation of plant matter, for example, generates an estimated 60 million tons/year.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide (CO) is present in small amounts (about 80 ppb) in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Most comes from chemical reactions with organic compounds emitted by human activities and natural origins due to photochemical reactions in the troposphere that generate about 5 × 1012 kilograms per year.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Other natural sources of CO include volcanoes, forest and bushfires, and other miscellaneous forms of combustion such as fossil fuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Small amounts are also emitted from the ocean, and from geological activity because carbon monoxide occurs dissolved in molten volcanic rock at high pressures in the Earth's mantle.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Because natural sources of carbon monoxide vary from year to year, it is difficult to accurately measure natural emissions of the gas.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has an indirect effect on radiative forcing by elevating concentrations of direct greenhouse gases, including methane and tropospheric ozone.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] CO can react chemically with other atmospheric constituents (primarily the hydroxyl radical, •OH) that would otherwise destroy methane.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Through natural processes in the atmosphere, it is oxidized to carbon dioxide and ozone.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is short-lived in the atmosphere (with an average lifetime of about one to two months), and spatially variable in concentration.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Due to its long lifetime in the mid-troposphere, carbon monoxide is also used as a tracer for pollutant plumes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Beyond Earth, carbon monoxide is the second-most common diatomic molecule in the interstellar medium, after molecular hydrogen.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Because of its asymmetry, this polar molecule produces far brighter spectral lines than the hydrogen molecule, making CO much easier to detect.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Interstellar CO was first detected with radio telescopes in 1970.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It is now the most commonly used tracer of molecular gas in general in the interstellar medium of galaxies, as molecular hydrogen can only be detected using ultraviolet light, which requires space telescopes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide observations provide much of the information about the molecular clouds in which most stars form.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Beta Pictoris, the second brightest star in the constellation Pictor, shows an excess of infrared emission compared to normal stars of its type, which is caused by large quantities of dust and gas (including carbon monoxide) near the star.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the atmosphere of Venus carbon monoxide occurs as a result of the photodissociation of carbon dioxide by electromagnetic radiation of wavelengths shorter than 169 nm.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It has also been identified spectroscopically on the surface of Neptune's moon Triton.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Solid carbon monoxide is a component of comets.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The volatile or "ice" component of Halley's Comet is about 15% CO.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] At room temperature and at normal atmospheric pressure, carbon monoxide is merely metastable (see Boudouard reaction) and the same is true at low temperatures where CO and CO2 are solid, but nevertheless it can exist for billions of years in comets.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] There is very little CO in the atmosphere of Pluto, which seems to have been formed from comets.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This may be because there is (or was) liquid water inside Pluto.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This is called the water-gas shift reaction when occurring in the gas phase, but it can also take place (very slowly) in an aqueous solution.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] These reactions can take place in a few million years even at temperatures such as found on Pluto.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Large CO pollution events can be observed from space over cities.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Along with aldehydes, carbon monoxide is part of the series of cycles of chemical reactions that form photochemical smog.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It reacts with hydroxyl radical (•OH) to produce a radical intermediate •HOCO, which rapidly transfers its radical hydrogen to O2 to form peroxy radical (HO2•) and carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Peroxy radical subsequently reacts with nitrogen oxide (NO) to form nitrogen dioxide (NO2) and hydroxyl radical.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] NO2 gives O(3P) via photolysis, thereby forming O3 following reaction with O2.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Although the creation of NO2 is the critical step leading to low-level ozone formation, it also increases this ozone in another, somewhat mutually exclusive way, by reducing the quantity of NO that is available to react with ozone.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is one of the most acutely toxic indoor air contaminants.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide may be emitted from tobacco smoke and generated from malfunctioning fuel burning stoves (wood, kerosene, natural gas, propane) and fuel burning heating systems (wood, oil, natural gas) and from blocked flues connected to these appliances.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In developed countries, the main sources of indoor CO emission come from cooking and heating devices that burn fossil fuels and are faulty, incorrectly installed, or poorly maintained.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Appliance malfunction may be due to faulty installation or lack of maintenance and proper use.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In low- and middle-income countries the most common sources of CO in homes are burning biomass fuels and cigarette smoke.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Miners refer to carbon monoxide as "whitedamp" or the "silent killer".
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It can be found in confined areas of poor ventilation in both surface mines and underground mines.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The most common sources of carbon monoxide in mining operations are the internal combustion engine and explosives; however, in coal mines, carbon monoxide can also be found due to the low-temperature oxidation of coal.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The idiom "Canary in the coal mine" pertained to an early warning of a carbon monoxide presence.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Acute exposure can also lead to long-term neurological effects such as cognitive and behavioural changes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Severe CO poisoning may lead to unconsciousness, coma, and death.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Chronic exposure to low concentrations of carbon monoxide may lead to lethargy, headaches, nausea, flu-like symptoms, and neuropsychological and cardiovascular issues.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has a wide range of functions across all disciplines of chemistry.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The four premier categories of reactivity involve metal-carbonyl catalysis, radical chemistry, cation and anion chemistries.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Most metals form coordination complexes containing covalently attached carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] These derivatives, called metal carbonyls, tend to be more robust when the metal is in lower oxidation states.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] For example, iron pentacarbonyl (Fe(CO)5) is an air-stable, distillable liquid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] These volatile complexes are often highly toxic.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Some metal–CO complexes are prepared by decarbonylation of organic solvents, not from CO.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] For instance, iridium trichloride and triphenylphosphine react in boiling 2-methoxyethanol or DMF to afford IrCl(CO)(PPh3)2.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] As a ligand, CO binds through carbon, forming a kind of triple bond.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The lone pair on the carbon atom donates electron density to form a M-CO sigma bond.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The two π* orbitals on CO bind to filled metal orbitals.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The effect is related to the Dewar-Chatt-Duncanson model.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The effects of the quasi-triple M-C bond is reflected in the infrared spectrum of these complexes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Whereas free CO vibrates at 2143 cm−1, its complexes tend to absorb near 1950 cm−1.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the presence of strong acids, alkenes react with carboxylic acids.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Hydrolysis of this species (an acylium ion) gives the carboxylic acid, a net process known as the Koch–Haaf reaction.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the Gattermann–Koch reaction, arenes are converted to benzaldehyde derivatives in the presence of CO, AlCl3, and HCl.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] A mixture of hydrogen gas and CO reacts with alkenes to give aldehydes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The process requires the presence of metal catalysts.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] With main group reagents, CO undergoes several noteworthy reactions.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Chlorination of CO is the industrial route to the important compound phosgene.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] With borane CO forms the adduct H3BCO, which is isoelectronic with the acylium cation [H3CCO]+.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] CO reacts with sodium to give products resulting from C−C coupling such as sodium acetylenediolate 2Na+·C2O2−2.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It reacts with molten potassium to give a mixture of an organometallic compound, potassium acetylenediolate 2K+·C2O2−2, potassium benzenehexolate 6K+·C6O6−6, and potassium rhodizonate 2K+·C6O2−6.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The compounds cyclohexanehexone or triquinoyl (C6O6) and cyclopentanepentone or leuconic acid (C5O5), which so far have been obtained only in trace amounts, can be regarded as polymers of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] At pressures exceeding 5 GPa, carbon monoxide converts to polycarbonyl, a solid polymer that is metastable at atmospheric pressure but is explosive.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is conveniently produced in the laboratory by the dehydration of formic acid or oxalic acid, for example with concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Thermal combustion is the most common source for carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Many methods have been developed for carbon monoxide production.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] A major industrial source of CO is producer gas, a mixture containing mostly carbon monoxide and nitrogen, formed by combustion of carbon in air at high temperature when there is an excess of carbon.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In an oven, air is passed through a bed of coke.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The initially produced CO2 equilibrates with the remaining hot carbon to give CO.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The reaction of CO2 with carbon to give CO is described as the Boudouard reaction.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Other similar "synthesis gases" can be obtained from natural gas and other fuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide can also be produced by high-temperature electrolysis of carbon dioxide with solid oxide electrolyzer cells.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] One method developed at DTU Energy uses a cerium oxide catalyst and does not have any issues of fouling of the catalyst.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is also produced by the direct oxidation of carbon in a limited supply of oxygen or air.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Since CO is a gas, the reduction process can be driven by heating, exploiting the positive (favorable) entropy of reaction.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The Ellingham diagram shows that CO formation is favored over CO2 in high temperatures.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is an industrial gas with many applications in bulk chemicals manufacturing.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Large quantities of aldehydes are produced by the hydroformylation reaction of alkenes, carbon monoxide, and H2.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Hydroformylation is coupled to the Shell higher olefin process to give precursors to detergents.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Phosgene, useful for preparing isocyanates, polycarbonates, and polyurethanes, is produced by passing purified carbon monoxide and chlorine gas through a bed of porous activated carbon, which serves as a catalyst.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] World production of this compound was estimated to be 2.74 million tonnes in 1989.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Methanol is produced by the hydrogenation of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In a related reaction, the hydrogenation of carbon monoxide is coupled to C−C bond formation, as in the Fischer–Tropsch process where carbon monoxide is hydrogenated to liquid hydrocarbon fuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This technology allows coal or biomass to be converted to diesel.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the Cativa process, carbon monoxide and methanol react in the presence of a homogeneous iridium catalyst and hydroiodic acid to give acetic acid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This process is responsible for most of the industrial production of acetic acid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is a strong reductive agent and has been used in pyrometallurgy to reduce metals from ores since ancient times.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide strips oxygen off metal oxides, reducing them to pure metal in high temperatures and forming carbon dioxide in the process.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is not usually supplied as is, in the gaseous phase, in the reactor, but rather it is formed in high temperature in presence of oxygen-carrying ore, or a carboniferous agent such as coke, and high temperature.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The blast furnace process is a typical example of a process of reduction of metal from ore with carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Likewise, blast furnace gas collected at the top of blast furnaces still contains some 10% to 30% of carbon monoxide, and is used as fuel on Cowper stoves and on Siemens-Martin furnaces on open hearth steelmaking.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has been proposed for use as a fuel on Mars by NASA researcher Geoffrey Landis.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Landis also proposed manufacturing the fuel from the similar carbon dioxide atmosphere of Venus for a sample return mission, in combination with solar-powered UAVs and rocket balloon ascent.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is used in electrochemistry to study the structure of electrodes thanks to its strong affinity to some metals used as electrocatalysts, through a technique known as CO stripping.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is a bioactive molecule which acts as a gaseous signaling molecule.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] It is naturally produced by many enzymatic and non-enzymatic pathways, the best understood of which is the catabolic action of heme oxygenase on the heme derived from hemoproteins such as hemoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Following the first report that carbon monoxide is a normal neurotransmitter in 1993, carbon monoxide has received significant clinical attention as a biological regulator.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Because of carbon monoxide's role in the body, abnormalities in its metabolism have been linked to a variety of diseases, including neurodegenerations, hypertension, heart failure, and pathological inflammation.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In many tissues, carbon monoxide acts as anti-inflammatory, vasodilatory, and encouragers of neovascular growth.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In animal model studies, carbon monoxide reduced the severity of experimentally induced bacterial sepsis, pancreatitis, hepatic ischemia/reperfusion injury, colitis, osteoarthritis, lung injury, lung transplantation rejection, and neuropathic pain while promoting skin wound healing.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Therefore, there is significant interest in the therapeutic potential of carbon monoxide becoming pharmaceutical agent and clinical standard of care.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Many laboratories worldwide have studied carbon monoxide for its anti-inflammatory and cytoprotective properties.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] These properties might be usable for preventing the development of a series of pathological conditions including ischemia reperfusion injury, transplant rejection, atherosclerosis, severe sepsis, severe malaria, or autoimmunity.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Many pharmaceutical drug delivery initiatives have developed methods to safely administer carbon monoxide, and subsequent controlled clinical trials have evaluated the therapeutic effect of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Microbiota may also utilize carbon monoxide as a gasotransmitter.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide sensing is a signaling pathway facilitated by proteins such as CooA.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The scope of the biological roles for carbon monoxide sensing is still unknown.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The human microbiome produces, consumes, and responds to carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] For example, in certain bacteria, carbon monoxide is produced via the reduction of carbon dioxide by the enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase with favorable bioenergetics to power downstream cellular operations.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In another example, carbon monoxide is a nutrient for methanogenic archaea which reduce it to methane using hydrogen.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide has certain antimicrobial properties which have been studied to treat against infectious diseases.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide is used in modified atmosphere packaging systems in the US, mainly with fresh meat products such as beef, pork, and fish to keep them looking fresh.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The benefit is two-fold: carbon monoxide protects against microbial spoilage and enhances the meat color for consumer appeal.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The carbon monoxide combines with myoglobin to form carboxymyoglobin, a bright-cherry-red pigment.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carboxymyoglobin is more stable than the oxygenated form of myoglobin, oxymyoglobin, which can become oxidized to the brown pigment metmyoglobin.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This stable red color can persist much longer than in normally packaged meat.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Typical levels of carbon monoxide used in the facilities that use this process are between 0.4% and 0.5%.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The technology was first given "generally recognized as safe" (GRAS) status by the U.S.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 2002 for use as a secondary packaging system, and requires no labeling.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In 2004, the FDA approved CO as primary packaging method, declaring that CO does not mask spoilage odor.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The process is currently unauthorized in many other countries, including Japan, Singapore, and the European Union.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In ancient history, Hannibal executed Roman prisoners with coal fumes during the Second Punic War.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide was used for genocide during the Holocaust at some extermination camps, the most notable by gas vans in Chełmno, and in the Action T4 "euthanasia" program.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Man has maintained a complex relationship with carbon monoxide since first learning to control fire circa 800,000 BC.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Early man probably discovered the toxicity of carbon monoxide poisoning upon introducing fire into his dwellings.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The early development of metallurgy and smelting technologies emerging circa 6,000 BC through the Bronze Age likewise plagued man from carbon monoxide exposure.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Apart from the toxicity of carbon monoxide, Native Americans in the United States may have experienced the neuroactive properties of carbon monoxide through shamanistic fireside rituals.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Early civilizations developed mythological tales to explain the origin of fire, such as Prometheus from Greek mythology who shared fire with humans.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Aristotle (384–322 BC) first recorded that burning coals produced toxic fumes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Greek physician Galen (AD 129–199) speculated that there was a change in the composition of the air that caused harm when inhaled, and many others of the era developed a basis of knowledge about carbon monoxide in the context of coal fume toxicity.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Cleopatra may have died from carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In 1697, Georg Ernst Stahl used *carbonarii halitus* to refer to toxic vapors thought to be carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Friedrich Hoffmann conducted the first modern scientific investigation into carbon monoxide poisoning from coal in 1716.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Herman Boerhaave conducted the first scientific experiments on the effect of carbon monoxide (coal fumes) on animals in the 1730s.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Joseph Priestley is considered to have first synthesized carbon monoxide in 1772.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carl Wilhelm Scheele similarly isolated carbon monoxide from charcoal in 1773 and thought it could be the carbonic entity making fumes toxic.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Torbern Bergman isolated carbon monoxide from oxalic acid in 1775.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] One year later, the French chemist de Lassone produced CO by heating zinc oxide with coke, but mistakenly identified the gaseous product as hydrogen, as it burned with a blue flame.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the presence of oxygen, including atmospheric concentrations, carbon monoxide burns with a blue flame, producing carbon dioxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Antoine Lavoisier conducted similarly inconclusive experiments in 1777.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The gas was identified as a compound containing carbon and oxygen by William Cruickshank in 1800.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Thomas Beddoes and James Watt recognized carbon monoxide (as hydrocarbonate) to brighten venous blood in 1793.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Watt suggested coal fumes could act as an antidote to the oxygen in blood, and Beddoes and Watt likewise suggested hydrocarbonate has a greater affinity for animal fiber than oxygen in 1796.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In 1854, Adrien Chenot similarly suggested carbon monoxide to remove the oxygen from blood and then be oxidized by the body to carbon dioxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] The mechanism for carbon monoxide poisoning is widely credited to Claude Bernard whose memoirs beginning in 1846 and published in 1857 phrased, "prevents arterials blood from becoming venous".
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Felix Hoppe-Seyler independently published similar conclusions in the following year.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Carbon monoxide gained recognition as an essential reagent in the 1900s.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Three industrial processes illustrate its evolution in industry.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In the Fischer–Tropsch process, coal and related carbon-rich feedstocks are converted into liquid fuels via the intermediacy of CO.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Developed as part of the German war effort to compensate for their lack of domestic petroleum, this technology continues today.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Also in Germany, a mixture of CO and hydrogen was found to combine with olefins to give aldehydes.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] This process, called hydroformylation, is used to produce many large scale chemicals such as surfactants as well as specialty compounds that are popular fragrances and drugs.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] For example, CO is used in the production of vitamin A.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] In a third major process, attributed to researchers at Monsanto, CO combines with methanol to give acetic acid.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Most acetic acid is produced by the Cativa process.
[src:carbon-monoxide/carbon-monoxide] Hydroformylation and the acetic acid syntheses are two of myriad carbonylation processes.
